LIVE: A statement by President Obama on Afghanistan is scheduled for 11 a.m. Eastern Time today.

Senior administration officials said the president will keep 5,500 U.S. troops in Afghanistan when he leaves office in 2017. They spoke on the condition of anonymity because they were not authorized to discuss the matter publicly ahead of the president.

Officials said he would outline plans to maintain the current force of 9,800 troops in Afghanistan through most of next year, then draw down to 5,500 troops in 2017, at a pace still to be determined by commanders.
link_name: Officials: Troops to remain in Afghanistan beyond 2016

The Army Public Health Command launched a study of the stimulant in 2012 after two soldiers, Pvt. Michael Sparling, 22, and Sgt. Demekia Cola, 31, died of heart failure during physical training in 2011 at Fort Bliss, Texas. The Army said DMAA use was a "contributing factor" in both deaths.

A third soldier, Pfc. David Artis, died in July 2012 of heatstroke; Army officials linked DMAA use to his death, as well.

"I stayed cool and tried to hit him in the face. I really wanted to finish him. He's long, he's rangy and I couldn't reach his chin. status_message: Six soldiers were disciplined for their roles in mistakenly burning hundreds of copies of the Koran in February but avoided court-martial. The investigation found the soldiers did not act with "malicious intent." In a separate incident, Marines depicted in a video showing them urinating on dead Taliban insurgents also got NJPs. Read more here:
link_name: No courts-martial in Koran, urination incidents

status_message: The U.S. Court of Appeals for the Armed Forces said that Maj. Nidal Hasan's appeal was premature because the trial judge hasn't issued a definitive, written order for the forced shaving. If the judge issues that order, then Hasan can appeal it, the court said.
link_name: Hood trial to go forward without beard ruling

status_message: Prosecutors in the murders of a former soldier and his girlfriend say four Fort Stewart-based soldiers killed the couple to conceal a plot by a militia group made up of current and former service members. The plot, said prosecutors, included taking over the Georgia Army base and overthrowing the government. Read more of the story here:
link_name: Prosecutor: Murder case uncovers terror plot

status_message: A 99-page investigative report by the DoD Inspector General's Office on 4-star Gen. William "Kip" Ward concluded he "engaged in multiple forms of misconduct related to official and unofficial travel." Ward denied committing any improprieties, according to the report. Defense Secretary Leon Panetta is expected to soon decide what action to take, which may include demotion. Read more here:
link_name: DoD details general's lavish spending

status_message: The Air Force is negotiating a trade of some of its newer helicopters for the Army's older ones in an effort to replace copters lost in combat.
link_name: Helo swap would help rebuild rescue fleet

status_message: Four soldiers were among the seven American casualties when a Black Hawk crashed in Afghanistan on Thursday.
link_name: Soldiers, SEALs among dead in Black Hawk crash

status_message: Gen. William "Kip" Ward, former AFRICOM chief, is under investigation for allegedly spending hundreds of thousands of dollars on lavish travel and hotels. Defense Secretary Leon Panetta is expected to make a final decision on the matter before the end of the month, according to several defense officials.
link_name: 4-star general investigated over spending

status_message: Maj. Nidal Hasan was scheduled to enter a plea Wednesday to charges in the attack at Fort Hood, but all court proceedings were put on hold while an appeals court considers his objections to being forcibly shaved.
link_name: Hood shooting trial put on hold over Hasan's beard

status_message: A spike in so-called green-on-blue attacks has prompted U.S. officials in Afghanistan to revamp the screening process for Afghan recruits and identify new ways to protect U.S. troops, officials said.
link_name: Inside-the-wire attacks double in Afghanistan

status_message: In a letter to Defense Secretary Leon Panetta, Rep. Duncan Hunter called for "fair and and due consideration" to a Medal of Honor nomination for Capt. Will Swenson. The California Republican compared Swenson's case to that of fallen Marine Sgt. Rafael Peralta, whose nomination was denied. Read more about this case here:
link_name: Congressman links Swenson, Peralta MoH cases

status_message: Spc. Ryan J. Offutt was demoted, received a bad conduct discharge and will serve 6 months in prison after he pleaded guilty to one count of hazing and two specifications of maltreatment in the death of 19-year-old Pvt. Danny Chen. Authorities say Chen shot himself last year in Afghanistan after being hazed over his ethnicity.
link_name: Soldier gets 6 months in Chen hazing case

status_message: The unemployment rate for veterans who entered service after Sept. 11, 2001, fell to 8.9 percent in July, down from 9.5 percent the previous month and from 12.4 percent in July 2011, according to the latest monthly employment report released Friday by the Labor Department's Bureau of Labor Statistics.
link_name: Vets' unemployment rate improves again in July

status_message: A review found Col. Dallas Homas, commander at Madigan Army Medical Center, "did not inappropriately influence PTSD diagnoses" but determined the system being used to diagnose soldiers was inappropriate for the military.
link_name: Army reinstates Madigan chief after PTSD probe

status_message: Daniel Rodriguez, a 24-year-old Army vet, was cleared as a walk-on receiver for Clemson. Chasing his dream of playing college football helps fulfill a promise to a brother-in-arms who was killed during a 2009 battle in Afghanistan.
link_name: Combat vet cleared to play football at Clemson

status_message: Sgt. Adam Holcomb was convicted Monday of maltreatment of a subordinate and assault in the alleged hazing death of Pvt. Danny Chen, who committed suicide. Holcomb was cleared of the most serious charge: negligent homicide. The Youngstown, Ohio, native received 30 days in prison and a demotion.
link_name: Sgt. sentenced in soldier's hazing suicide

status_message: Military pay and benefits will be exempt from sequestration, but cuts to other defense programs will be deeper if the across-the-board budget cuts happen in January, the White House budget office announced.

status_message: Since 2001, personnel costs have climbed at a rate of about $4,000 per person per year. That figure is expected to rise by an average of $4,700 a year over the next several years, despite Defense Department efforts to hold down costs.

status_message: The DoD has identified the six soldiers killed in an Afghanistan IED blast Sunday. The fallen were all MPs from Fort Bliss.

status_message: The Manufacturing Skills Standards Council is looking for 200 active-duty volunteers who plan to separate from the military to participate in a pilot program for logistics certification. The council will pay the $100 per-person cost for the volunteers' certification exams, which could give them a leg up for more than 5 million jobs.
link_name: Troops sought for job certification project
WTUs will be around long after wars' end

status_message: The family of a soldier who was killed in Afghanistan has sued a firm hired by the U.S. military to screen guards providing security at bases. The wrongful death lawsuit alleges the Canadian firm rehired an Afghan national after he supposedly made threats to attack U.S. troops. Rudy Acosta was among the two dead and four injured in the attack.
link_name: Family of soldier sues security screening firm
